-- Crude Options Volatility Falls as Futures Reach Six-Day High
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-04-10T18:57:12Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-10/crude-options-volatility-falls-as-futures-reach-six-day-high.html
Crude options volatility fell a
fourth straight day as the underlying futures reached the
highest level in six days.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
June, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 18.96 percent at 2:31 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , down from 19.24 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for June delivery rose 46
cents to $94.97 a barrel on the Nymex, the highest settlement
since April 2.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
May $90 puts, which fell 5 cents to 8 cents a barrel on volume
of 2,168 contracts at 2:46 p.m. July $110 calls were the second-
most active, rising 1 cent to 15 cents of volume of 1,378
contracts.  Puts accounted for 51 percent of electronic trading volume
today and 55 percent of yesterdayâ€™s volume of 129,011 contracts.  June $80 puts were the most active options traded in the
previous session, with 9,608 contracts changing hands. They
declined 1 cent to 8 cents a barrel. June $90 puts fell 23 cents
to 84 cents on 7,875 lots.  Open interest was highest for May $85 puts with 38,641
contracts. Next were June $80 puts with 36,470 and December $105
calls at 36,407.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-
outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
